{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17652174","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17652174"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:33:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:33:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18515"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18515","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18515"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.27,0.09,0.27,0.02,0.36]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11244"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76344"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11244","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11244"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18515"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61853"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7429"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26067"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26283"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76344","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76344"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe blood supply to the femoral head and neck is critical for maintaining bone viability. Multiple arterial sources contribute to this supply through a complex anastomotic network.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following arteries provides the primary blood supply to the femoral head?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lateral circumflex femoral artery","Superior gluteal artery","Obturator artery","First perforating artery","Medial circumflex femoral artery"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emedial circumflex femoral artery\u003C/strong\u003E (Image) is the principal blood supply to the femoral head. It gives off retinacular branches that penetrate the hip joint capsule to supply the femoral head. This vessel typically arises from the profunda femoris artery or occasionally directly from the femoral artery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELateral circumflex femoral artery\u003C/strong\u003E primarily supplies the greater trochanter and surrounding muscles rather than the femoral head\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuperior gluteal artery\u003C/strong\u003E supplies the gluteal muscles and provides only minor contributions to the femoral head through anastomoses\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObturator artery\u003C/strong\u003E contributes minimally to femoral head blood supply through small branches\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFirst perforating artery\u003C/strong\u003E supplies the femoral shaft but not the femoral head\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding this blood supply is clinically important as disruption can lead to avascular necrosis of the femoral head, particularly following femoral neck fractures or hip dislocation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The medial circumflex femoral artery provides the main blood supply to the femoral head via its retinacular branches.","The lateral circumflex femoral artery primarily supplies the greater trochanter and surrounding muscles.","Disruption of the medial circumflex femoral artery can lead to avascular necrosis of the femoral head."],"referenc